[normal]1.3
[normal]              
[normal]The possible effect of the sun on the climate
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Th
[normal]e IPCC d
[normal]ismisses 
[normal]the effect of 
[normal]the sun on the clim
[normal]ate because it limits 
[normal]its analysis to solar irradiance
[normal], which only changes by 0.1% across the 11 year solar cycle
[normal].  But this is only part of the 
[normal]sun’s 
[normal]story. 
[normal]“
[normal]In the subdomain of irradiation, strong fluctuations do indeed occur, of up to 70%.  Ultraviolet 
[normal]light is converted to heat in the ozone layer and ionosphere and, as a result, leads to a formidable temperature rollercoaster with magnitudes of change reaching several degrees Celsius – all synchronized with the 11-year solar cycle…Furthermore, the sun’s
[normal] magnetic field also fluctuates in sync with the 11-year solar cycles, and all this has a profound impact of 10-20% on cosmic rays…These cosmic particles seed clouds in the lower atmosphere, which cool the earth.  
[normal]In other words, intense solar activity lea[bold]ds to less cloud cover, resulting in more warming, whereas weak solar activity leads to more cloud cover and so causes cooling[bold]…”[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]A recent NASA press release comments:-
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“
[normal]There is, however, a dawning realization among researchers that even these 
[normal]apparently tiny variations can have a significant effect on terrestrial climate. A new report issued by the National Research Council (NRC), “The Effects of Solar Variability on Earth’s Climate,” lays out some of the surprisingly complex ways that solar ac
[normal]tivity can make itself felt on our planet.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A new paper by two Dutchmen at the Space Research Organisation of the Netherlands “found that that during the major part of the four centuries investigated, i.e. the period 1610 till
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] around
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 1900 – 1950 , the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]average terrestrial ground temperatures depend solely on solar magnetic field variations.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Jasper Kirby, Head of fthe CLOUD Experiment at CERN, recently gave a thorough review showing strong  correlations between cosmic rays, solar cycles and earth’s clim
[normal]ate.  He projects a possible mini ice age by 2015 similar to the Dalton or Maunder minimum.
