[normal]The possible effect of the sun o
[normal]n
[normal] the climate
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Th
[normal]e IPCC d
[normal]ismisses 
[normal]the effect of 
[normal]the sun on the climate because it limits 
[normal]its analysis to solar irradiance
[normal], which only changes by 0.1% across the 11 year solar cycle
[normal].  But this is only part of the 
[normal]su
[normal]n
[normal]’s 
[normal]story.  
[normal]In “The Neglected Sun”, recently published by Professor Fritz Vahrenholt
[normal] and 
[normal]Sebastian Lüning
[normal], the authors point out 
[normal]“ the IPCC “
[normal]overlooks a crucial detail.  In the subdomain of irradiation, strong fluctuations do indeed occur, of up to 70%.  Ultraviolet light is converted to heat in the ozone layer and ionosphere and, as a result
[normal], leads to a formidable temperature rollercoaster with magnitudes of change reaching several degrees Celsius – all synchronized with the 11-year solar cycle…Furthermore, the sun’s magnetic field also fluctuates in sync with the 11-year solar cycles, and al
[normal]l this has a profound impact of 10-20% on cosmic rays…These cosmic particles seed clouds in the lower atmosphere, which cool the earth.  
[normal]In other words, intense solar activity leads to less cloud cover, resulting in more warming, whereas weak solar activit[bold]y leads to more cloud cover and so causes cooling[bold] (emboldening added)[bold]…[bold]And just a few per cent variation in cloud cover results in a change in the earth’s irradiative energy budget equal to the projected amount of the warming the IPCC claims that anthropoge
[normal]nic CO2 causes.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“Fluctuations in solar activity are manifested over a wide range of cycles and have characteristic cycle lengths of between 11 and 2,300 years. 
[normal]Especially important in today’s context is the 1000 year cycle, which led to unusually high ir[bold]radiation intensities during the second half of the twentieth century. Over recent decades, the sun has been in one of its most active phases of the last 10,000 years.  Solar magnetic field activity more than doubled between 1901 and 1995.  Similar irradia[bold]tion maximums occurred 1,000 years ago (the Medieval warm period) and 2000 years ago (the Roman warm period).  In both periods, pronounced climate warming took place.  The Roman warm period, the Medieval warm period and today’s Modern Optimum (since 1850) [bold]are well documented.  Between those warm periods the sun’s activity decreased and this led to distinct cold phases – the Vandal Cold Period and the Little Ice Age[bold]…”[bold](emboldening added)[bold]&#xa0;[bold]“We are by no means claiming that CO2 has had no impact on today’s 
[normal]climate events.  However, we are able to show that at least half of the warming of the last 30 years can be attributed to the sun and oceanic oscillations.  CO2 could be responsible for the other half of the warming, but its share may be even less than tha
[normal]t…Taking both the important natural and anthropogenic climate factors into account, we can expect a slight cooling of about 0.2-
[normal]0.3
[normal]0
[normal]C
[normal] by the year 2035.  Only cooling can be expected from the sun over the coming decades.”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A recent NASA press release commen
[normal]ts:-
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“
[normal]There is, however, a dawning realization among researchers that even these apparently tiny variations can have a significant effect on terrestrial climate. A new report issued by the National Research Council (NRC), “The Effects of Solar Variability
[normal] on Earth’s Climate,” lays out some of the surprisingly complex ways that solar activity can make itself felt on our planet.
[normal]”
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A new paper by two Dutchmen at the Space Research Organisation of the Netherlands “found that 
[normal]that during the major part of the f
[normal]our centuries investigated, i.e. the period 1610 till
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] around
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 1900 – 1950 , the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] average terrestrial ground temperatures depend solely on solar magnetic field variations. After 1900 there is an increasing excess in the temperature which is ascribed to ant
[normal]hropogenic
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] activity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] After the impressive Grand Maximum of the 20th century the sun went through an exceptional
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] not before observed phase transition that lasted relatively long, i.e. from about 2005 till 
[normal]2010.”
